nging patterns of identification in the U.S. population, influence our understanding of patterns and trends in racial and ethnic inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aEthnicityzUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aafrican americans.  aamerican indians.  aanthropologist.  aclassroom education.  aculture.  aeducation.  afamily.  agender.  ahispanics.  aimmigration.  amexican americans.  apolitical activist.  arace relations.  arace.  aracial and ethnic inequality.  aracism in america.  asocioeconomic inequalities.  asociologist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028692440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520961975?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961975/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY